{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540009"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:49:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:49:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16727"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16727"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.02,0.22,0.37,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9418"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89892"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9418"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16727"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74061"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"2219"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22280"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30616"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43646"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89892"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-year history of productive cough and progressive breathlessness. He works as a grain silo operator and has been in this role for 15 years. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has a five pack-year smoking history and continues to smoke two to three cigarettes per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 128/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals scattered wheeze throughout both lung fields. Peak expiratory flow rate is 380 L/min (predicted 520 L/min). Pulmonary function testing has been arranged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Workplace exposure assessment","Home peak flow monitoring","Smoking cessation counselling","High-resolution chest CT scan","Inhaled corticosteroid therapy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of occupational chronic bronchitis, given his long-term exposure to grain dust. While he has a smoking history, it is relatively light, and his occupational exposure is likely the primary contributor to his symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWorkplace exposure assessment\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as it helps identify specific hazards and evaluate the adequacy of existing control measures. This assessment can guide recommendations for engineering controls, administrative controls, or personal protective equipment to prevent further exposure and disease progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmoking cessation counselling\u003C/strong\u003E, while important as smoking can amplify the effects of occupational exposures, is not the primary intervention needed given his light smoking history and significant occupational exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-resolution chest CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E might be useful later to evaluate for structural changes or alternative diagnoses, but the initial focus should be on establishing the relationship between workplace exposure and symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHome peak flow monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E could help document work-related changes in lung function but would not be the first step in management. This might be implemented after the workplace assessment to document exposure-response relationships.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhaled corticosteroid therapy\u003C/strong\u003E might help manage symptoms but does not address the underlying cause. Treatment without addressing workplace exposure would allow the condition to progress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOccupational chronic bronchitis is primarily caused by workplace exposure to dusts, fumes, and other respiratory irritants, though smoking can exacerbate the condition. Prevention through workplace controls is the cornerstone of management, along with regular monitoring and appropriate use of personal protective equipment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Occupational chronic bronchitis can develop in workers exposed to dust, fumes, and irritants, with risk amplified by cigarette smoking.","A thorough occupational history is essential in evaluating chronic respiratory symptoms.","Prevention through workplace controls and personal protective equipment is crucial in managing occupational chronic bronchitis."],"references":["Kongsupon N, Walters GI, Sadhra SS. Occupational causes of hypersensitivity pneumonitis: a systematic review and compendium. Occup Med (Lond). 2021 Oct 1;71(6-7):255-259. doi: 10.1093/occmed/kqab082. PMID: 34370035; PMCID: PMC8486273. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34370035/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74061"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16727"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"item